    <statement><p>Add or subtract the rational expressions to a single rational expression and then simplify. If applicable, state the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{5}{r+4}+\frac{1}{r-3}} =}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{6r-11}{\left(r+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{5}{r+4}+\frac{1}{r-3}} 
      \amp = {\frac{5}{r+4}} \cdot \frac{(r - 3)}{(r - 3)} +\frac{1}{r - 3} \cdot \frac{(r+4)}{(r+4)}  \\
      \amp = {\frac{5\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)+r+4}{\left(r+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{5r-15+r+4}{\left(r+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{6r-11}{\left(r+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
</solution>
